[?25l[0m[?25l[0m[0m[38;5;12mI'll share my reasoning process[0m[38;5;244m (using tool: thinking)[0m: This is very valuable. The kiro-cli has:
1. `--no-interactive` - runs without user input
2. `--resume-id <SESSION_ID>` - resume a specific conversation
3. `--agent <AGENT>` - select agent profile
4. `--trust-all-tools` - auto-approve all tools
5. `--wrap never` - raw output
6. `--require-mcp-startup` - ensure MCP servers start
7. `[INPUT]` - the first question to ask

The key insight for persistent agents is the `--resume-id` flag. You can:
1. Start a session with `kiro-cli chat --no-interactive --agent bible-expert --trust-all-tools "Your initial task"`
2. Then send follow-up messages to the SAME session with `kiro-cli chat --no-interactive --resume-id <SESSION_ID> --trust-all-tools "Next task"`

This means you DON'T need a truly persistent process. You can:
- Start a session once (gets a session ID)
- Send subsequent work items to the same session via --resume-id
- The session maintains context across calls
- Context compaction happens automatically

This is the "repeated --no-interactive calls with shared state" pattern but with NATIVE session support!

Now let me also check if there's a way to pipe stdin for interactive mode. But the --resume-id pattern is probably the best approach.

Let me now write up the findings.

